\section{Model Structure}

\begin{frame}{A Model-Based Approach}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Unsupervised clustering can miss the generative story
    \item Need to incorporate:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Population-level patterns
        \item Individual predilection due to genetics
        \item New specific data (diagnoses from EHR)
    \end{itemize}
    \item Bayes theorem provides the foundation:
    \begin{align*}
    P(\Pi | \text{data}) \propto P(\text{data} | \Pi) \cdot P(\Pi)
    \end{align*}
\end{itemize}

\note{The crux of Bayes theorem is to combine new specific data with the prior belief based on universal patterns.
In this case, our ‘new’ data is the streaming set of updated diagnoses acquired from the EHR for a given patient
The prior here combines population-level patterns of disease occurrence over time with our naive estimation of an individual’s underlying signature predilection centered around germline genetic variation.To accomplish all these goals, we adopted a model-based approach in building our new method, Aladynoulli. It’s beauty is the ability to describe the generative story in math that we can then approach computationally. The Greeks help us follow biology to inference, and so it's worth taking a moment to understand the intricacy that we have created
}

\end{frame}

